 The correct approach to this question involves understanding that the height of the box is composed of the diameters of the three balls stacked on top of each other. Let the radius of each ball be $r$. The height of the box is equal to the sum of the diameters of the three balls, which is $3(2r) = 6r$. Given that the height of the box is $13.5 \text{ cm}$, we have:

\begin{align*}
6r &= 13.5 \Rightarrow \\
r &= \frac{13.5}{6} = 2.25
\end{align*}

The circumference of a circle is given by $C = 2\pi r$. Substituting the value of $r$ we find:

\begin{align*}
C &= 2\pi \cdot 2.25 = \frac{9}{2} \pi \text{ cm}
\end{align*}

